18/11/2008
THE HAGUE, Netherlands -- The International Court of Justice (ICJ) agreed on Tuesday (November 18th) to hear Croatia's allegations of genocide against Serbia during the early 1990s. Judges at the UN's highest court in The Hague voted 10-7 that it has jurisdiction in the case.Croatian sources say 20,000 Croatians died in the conflict, while hundreds of thousands of Serbs living there were displaced.This will be only the second genocide case to come before the ICJ. The first was also brought against Serbia, by Bosnia and Herezegovina. Serbia was cleared in that instance. A date for hearing Croatia's complaint has not been set. (BBC - 18/11/08) 
